Persist Groq daily-limit fallback across requests until midnight UTC

Previously the fallback chain re-tried every model from scratch on every
request, so a model that hit its daily token quota got re-tested each time,
wasting time and causing duplicate errors.

Changes to groq_ai.py:

New helpers at module level (persist for the bot process lifetime):
  _daily_exhausted: dict[str, float]   — model -> timestamp of exhaustion
  _mark_daily_exhausted(model)         — record a model as day-quota-hit
  _is_daily_exhausted(model) -> bool   — checks vs next midnight UTC; clears
                                         the entry automatically once expired
  _is_daily_limit_error(err) -> bool   — detects "per_day/daily/tokens_per_day/
                                         day limit/24-hour" in the error string

Error handler in the fallback loop:
  - When a 429/rate_limit error fires AND _is_daily_limit_error() is True
    → call _mark_daily_exhausted() instead of sleeping and retrying
  - Per-minute spikes (no daily keyword) still get the 2-second sleep

models_to_try filtering before the loop:
  - Any model in _daily_exhausted that hasn't cleared is stripped from the list
  - Logs which models were skipped
  - Result: subsequent requests start directly from the next available model
